# AutoStream Social-to-Lead AI Agent

This project is part of the ServiceHive â€“ Inflx ML Intern Assignment. The agent converts
social media conversations into qualified business leads using intent detection,
retrieval-augmented generation, and stateful lead capture.

--

# How to Run the Project Locally


git clone https://github.com/karkilalit18/Capstone-Project/blob/main/_Social-to-Lead%20Agentic%20Workflow.ipynb

cd autostream-agent

pip install -r requirements.txt




This project uses an AutoGen-style agentic workflow implemented in Python. AutoGen was
chosen because it supports multi-step conversational agents with memory and tool
execution, making it ideal for building real-world SaaS lead-generation systems.

The agent is composed of three main components. First, an intent detection module
classifies user messages into greeting, product inquiry, or high-intent lead using
keyword-based NLP logic. Second, a lightweight RAG pipeline retrieves pricing and policy
information from a local JSON knowledge base, ensuring responses are grounded in verified
company data. Third, a stateful lead capture workflow maintains conversation context across
multiple turns. Once a high-intent signal is detected, the agent enters a gated flow where
it sequentially collects the userâ€™s name, email, and creator platform. Only after all
three values are collected does it execute the mock_lead_capture() tool, preventing
premature API calls.

ðŸ“² WhatsApp Integration Using Webhooks

To deploy this agent on WhatsApp, Twilioâ€™s WhatsApp Business API can be used. Incoming user 
messages are sent to a FastAPI webhook endpoint. Each WhatsApp user ID is mapped to a
persistent agent state stored in memory or Redis. The webhook forwards the message to the
AutoStream agent, and the generated response is returned to the user through Twilioâ€™s API,
enabling real-time conversational lead generation on WhatsApp.
